The following topics are either addressed in the Emergency Response Plan for the Lompoc Oil and Gas Plant or available at the facility as part of FM O&G’s Emergency Response Program:

•	Public and agency notification requirements;
•	Emergency medical care and local hospital information;	
•	List of emergency equipment including location and;
•	Employee emergency response training;
•	Revision procedures and update requirements. 
4.1.1 Incident Command System (ICS)
FM O&G response operations will be managed and directed by personnel using the Incident Command System (ICS) which is used by most public agencies, including fire departments, U.S. Coast Guard, Department of Fish & Wildlife, etc. During an incident or an  
emergency, the first responder will initially act as the Incident Commander (IC), and the level of response may be escalated based on the judgement of the IC at the time.  The first responder and subsequent line managers are expected, and fully empowered by FM O&G relieved by a person of higher authority.   FM O&G endorses the principle of “over responding”, and employees should not hesitate to engage whatever resources are necessary to effectively mitigate an emergency.  


4.1.2 Emergency Response Coordination

Emergency response activities for the Lompoc Oil and Gas Plant are coordinated with Santa Barbara County Fire Department and Unified command will be established with Santa Barbara County Fire Department and California Department of Fish and Wildlife Office
